  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Establishes global standards for preventing money laundering\n- Recommends legal and regulatory measures\n- 39 member jurisdictions collaborate on anti-money laundering efforts\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigations\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n- Promotes transparency in financial transactions\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Helps countries develop anti-money laundering regulations\n- Provides technical assistance and monitoring\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Many countries have specific anti-money laundering legislation\n- Examples include:\n  - U.S. Bank Secrecy Act\n  - European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n  - UK's Proceeds of Crime Act\n\nThese international efforts aim to prevent criminal organizations from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.\n\nPenalties can include significant fines, asset seizure, and criminal prosecution for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering.",
